<h2>
    Tactics &amp; Techniques
</h2>
<ul>
    <li>
        <strong>Drift fishing:</strong> Roe under floats with drift or euro rigs 
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Swinging flies:</strong> Spey, egg, or leech patterns are effective in seams
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Plunking fools like spinners or plugs</strong> around current seams and eddies
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Centerpin fishing</strong> offers natural drifts on rivers like the Willamette&nbsp;
    </li>
</ul>
<h2>
    Access &amp; Platforms
</h2>
<ul>
    <li>
        <strong>Bank Fishing:</strong> Great opportunities at Clackamas parks, Sandy River access sites, and Willamette’s Meldrum Bar
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Drift Boats &amp; Kayaks:</strong> Commonly launched from Clackamas (McIver, Carver), Sandy (Oxbow), Columbia (boat ramps)&nbsp;
    </li>
</ul>
<h2>
    Quick Summary
</h2>
<ul>
    <li>
        <strong>Clackamas River</strong> — Best overall: multiple parks, boat ramps, overlapping winter/summer runs
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Sandy River</strong> — Scenic with diverse access and reliable spring-summer fish
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Willamette River</strong> — Urban fishery with solid winter steelhead opportunity
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Columbia River</strong> — Best for summer steelhead from boat launches and beaches
    </li>
</ul>

